AIVA — MOBILE PDF VIEWER + BACK BUTTON SAFETY
Read the ENTIRE prompt before making any changes.

═══════════════════════════════════════════
TWO PROBLEMS
═══════════════════════════════════════════

PROBLEM 1: PDFs don't render on mobile.
Mobile Safari and Chrome can't display PDFs in <iframe> tags. 
Users see a blank panel or a "download" link, requiring them to 
open the PDF in an external app. This breaks the Loku flow.

PROBLEM 2: Pressing "back" on mobile logs the user out.
The app is an SPA with no browser history management. When a 
modal/panel is open and the user presses the hardware back button, 
the browser navigates away from the app entirely instead of 
closing the panel.

═══════════════════════════════════════════
FIX 1: CANVAS-BASED PDF RENDERING
═══════════════════════════════════════════

Replace the <iframe> in DocumentPreviewPanel.tsx with a canvas-
based PDF renderer using pdf.js (via CDN, no npm install needed).

## Step 1: Add pdf.js script to index.html

In index.html, add these two script tags BEFORE the closing 
</body> tag (but before the module script):

```html
<script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/pdf.js/4.0.379/pdf.min.mjs" type="module"></script>
<script>
    // Make pdfjsLib available globally for the preview panel
    window.pdfjsLibReady = import('https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/pdf.js/4.0.379/pdf.min.mjs').then(lib => {
        lib.GlobalWorkerOptions.workerSrc = 'https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/pdf.js/4.0.379/pdf.worker.min.mjs';
        window.pdfjsLib = lib;
        return lib;
    });
</script>
```

## Step 2: Replace iframe with PdfCanvasViewer in DocumentPreviewPanel.tsx

Add this component ABOVE the DocumentPreviewPanel component in the 
same file:

```tsx
// ─── PDF Canvas Renderer (works on mobile) ───
const PdfCanvasViewer: React.FC<{ url: string }> = ({ url }) => {
    const containerRef = React.useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null);
    const [pageCount, setPageCount] = useState(0);
    const [currentPage, setCurrentPage] = useState(1);
    const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
    const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);
    const [pdfDoc, setPdfDoc] = useState<any>(null);
    const [scale, setScale] = useState(1.5);
    const canvasRefs = React.useRef<Map<number, HTMLCanvasElement>>(new Map());

    // Load PDF document
    useEffect(() => {
        let cancelled = false;
        setLoading(true);
        setError(null);

        const loadPdf = async () => {
            try {
                // Wait for pdfjsLib to be ready
                const lib = await (window as any).pdfjsLibReady;
                if (!lib) throw new Error('PDF.js not loaded');

                const loadingTask = lib.getDocument(url);
                const doc = await loadingTask.promise;

                if (cancelled) return;
                setPdfDoc(doc);
                setPageCount(doc.numPages);
                setLoading(false);
            } catch (err: any) {
                if (cancelled) return;
                console.error('[PdfViewer] Load error:', err);
                setError('Could not load PDF');
                setLoading(false);
            }
        };

        loadPdf();
        return () => { cancelled = true; };
    }, [url]);

    // Render a single page to canvas
    const renderPage = React.useCallback(async (pageNum: number, canvas: HTMLCanvasElement) => {
        if (!pdfDoc || !canvas) return;

        try {
            const page = await pdfDoc.getPage(pageNum);
            const viewport = page.getViewport({ scale });

            canvas.height = viewport.height;
            canvas.width = viewport.width;

            const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
            if (!ctx) return;

            await page.render({
                canvasContext: ctx,
                viewport: viewport,
            }).promise;
        } catch (err) {
            console.warn(`[PdfViewer] Page ${pageNum} render failed:`, err);
        }
    }, [pdfDoc, scale]);

    // Render visible pages
    useEffect(() => {
        if (!pdfDoc) return;

        // Render all pages (for scrollable view)
        for (let i = 1; i <= pageCount; i++) {
            const canvas = canvasRefs.current.get(i);
            if (canvas) renderPage(i, canvas);
        }
    }, [pdfDoc, pageCount, renderPage]);

    if (loading) {
        return (
            <div className="w-full h-full flex flex-col items-center justify-center gap-3">
                <div className="w-8 h-8 border-2 border-teal-500 border-t-transparent rounded-full animate-spin" />
                <p className="text-[10px] font-bold text-slate-400 uppercase tracking-widest">Loading document...</p>
            </div>
        );
    }

    if (error) {
        return (
            <div className="w-full h-full flex flex-col items-center justify-center gap-4 p-8">
                <FileText className="w-12 h-12 text-slate-300" />
                <p className="text-sm text-slate-500">{error}</p>
                <a href={url} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
                   className="px-5 py-2.5 bg-teal-600 text-white text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest rounded-xl">
                    Open Externally
                </a>
            </div>
        );
    }

    return (
        <div ref={containerRef} className="w-full h-full overflow-auto bg-slate-200 dark:bg-slate-900 p-4 space-y-4">
            {/* Page navigation bar */}
            <div className="sticky top-0 z-10 flex items-center justify-center gap-3 py-2 px-4 bg-white/90 dark:bg-slate-800/90 backdrop-blur-sm rounded-xl shadow-sm">
                <span className="text-[9px] font-bold text-slate-500 uppercase tracking-widest">
                    {pageCount} {pageCount === 1 ? 'page' : 'pages'}
                </span>
                <div className="w-px h-4 bg-slate-200" />
                <button 
                    onClick={() => setScale(s => Math.max(0.5, s - 0.25))}
                    className="p-1.5 rounded-lg hover:bg-slate-100 text-slate-400 text-[10px] font-bold"
                >
                    −
                </button>
                <span className="text-[9px] font-mono text-slate-400 w-10 text-center">
                    {Math.round(scale * 100)}%
                </span>
                <button 
                    onClick={() => setScale(s => Math.min(3, s + 0.25))}
                    className="p-1.5 rounded-lg hover:bg-slate-100 text-slate-400 text-[10px] font-bold"
                >
                    +
                </button>
            </div>

            {/* Rendered pages */}
            {Array.from({ length: pageCount }, (_, i) => i + 1).map(pageNum => (
                <div key={pageNum} className="flex justify-center">
                    <canvas
                        ref={el => { if (el) canvasRefs.current.set(pageNum, el); }}
                        className="shadow-lg rounded-sm bg-white max-w-full"
                        style={{ width: '100%', height: 'auto' }}
                    />
                </div>
            ))}
        </div>
    );
};
```

## Step 3: Replace the iframe in the CONTENT AREA

In DocumentPreviewPanel, find this block:

```tsx
{isPdf ? (
    /* PDF: render in iframe — browsers have built-in PDF viewers */
    <iframe
        src={`${file.public_url}#toolbar=1&navpanes=0`}
        className="w-full h-full border-0"
        title={displayName}
    />
```

Replace with:

```tsx
{isPdf ? (
    /* PDF: canvas-based rendering (works on mobile) */
    <PdfCanvasViewer url={file.public_url} />
```

═══════════════════════════════════════════
FIX 2: BACK BUTTON CLOSES PANELS
═══════════════════════════════════════════

When any full-screen overlay opens (DocumentHub, MediaViewerModal, 
DocumentPreviewPanel, AivaVisionCapture), push a history state. 
When back is pressed, catch the popstate event and close the 
overlay instead of navigating away.

## Step 1: Create a reusable hook

Add this to a new file `hooks/useBackButtonClose.ts` OR add it 
directly at the top of DocumentPreviewPanel.tsx (above the 
component):

```typescript
const useBackButtonClose = (isOpen: boolean, onClose: () => void) => {
    useEffect(() => {
        if (!isOpen) return;

        // Push a dummy state so "back" pops it instead of leaving
        const stateKey = `panel-${Date.now()}`;
        window.history.pushState({ panel: stateKey }, '');

        const handlePopState = (e: PopStateEvent) => {
            // Back was pressed — close the panel instead of navigating
            onClose();
        };

        window.addEventListener('popstate', handlePopState);

        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('popstate', handlePopState);
            // If closing normally (not via back button), clean up the history entry
            // Check if our state is still on top
            if (window.history.state?.panel === stateKey) {
                window.history.back();
            }
        };
    }, [isOpen, onClose]);
};
```

## Step 2: Use the hook in DocumentPreviewPanel

Inside DocumentPreviewPanel, add after the existing useEffects:

```typescript
useBackButtonClose(!!file, onClose);
```

## Step 3: Use the hook in DocumentHub

In DocumentHub.tsx, add the same hook:

```typescript
useBackButtonClose(isOpen, onClose);
```

## Step 4: Use the hook in MediaViewerModal

In MediaViewerModal.tsx, find the component and add:

```typescript
useBackButtonClose(!!activeMediaUrl, onCloseMedia);
```

Where `onCloseMedia` is whatever function closes the modal. 
Check the existing close handler name and use that.

NOTE: If the hook is defined in each file individually, just copy
the function into each file above the component. If you prefer a 
shared hook file, create `hooks/useBackButtonClose.ts` and import 
from there. Either approach works.

═══════════════════════════════════════════
IMPORTANT: KEEP DESKTOP PDF EXPERIENCE
═══════════════════════════════════════════

The canvas renderer works on BOTH desktop and mobile, so we're 
replacing iframe universally. The canvas approach actually gives 
us MORE control (zoom, page count display) than the browser's 
built-in PDF viewer.

If you want to keep the iframe on desktop as a fallback, you can 
detect mobile:

```typescript
const isMobile = /iPhone|iPad|iPod|Android/i.test(navigator.userAgent);
```

And conditionally render iframe vs canvas. But the canvas approach 
works well everywhere, so a universal replacement is cleaner.

